{"id":"39b8198f-31f2-48bf-9c55-f391d1f7ae45","timestamp":"2026-03-25T10:22:39.333309334Z","session_id":"17957061-a31f-4313-a5cc-251c94b6b8c4","agent_id":null,"agent_role":null,"task_id":null,"action":"PlanCreated","tool_name":null,"params":null,"risk_level":null,"decision":null,"result_success":null,"result_output":"{\"problem_statement\":\"what services are running on this machine\",\"analysis\":\"Step 1: Problem Analysis\\n- The user is asking for a comprehensive inventory of services running on the machine, which is a foundational system administration task.\\n- Components involved: systemd (or other init systems), process table, network services, container runtimes, and possibly application-specific services.\\n- Information needed: current init system, running processes, listening ports, containerized services, and systemd units (if applicable).\\n\\nStep 2: Hypothesis Generation\\n- H1: System uses systemd (most common on modern Linux) - confirmed by checking for systemctl.\\n- H2: Multiple container runtimes (Docker, Podman) might be present - confirmed by checking for docker/podman processes.\\n- H3: Traditional init systems (SysV, upstart) might be in use on older systems - confirmed by checking for service command or /etc/init.d.\\n- H4: Network services might be running but not showing in standard service lists - confirmed by checking listening ports.\\n\\nStep 3: Efficient Investigation Strategy\\n1. First identify the init system to determine the primary service management method.\\n2. Check running processes to see all active services, including those not managed by init system.\\n3. Check network services to identify what's listening on ports.\\n4. Check for containerized services as they might not appear in standard service lists.\\n5. All checks are read-only and can be done in parallel after init system identification.\",\"roles\":[{\"role_name\":\"System Services Auditor\",\"expertise\":[\"systemd\",\"init systems\",\"process analysis\"],\"responsibility\":\"Identify the init system and enumerate all system-managed services\",\"allowed_tools\":[\"shell\",\"log_reader\"],\"token_budget\":50000,\"target_host\":null},{\"role_name\":\"Network Services Investigator\",\"expertise\":[\"networking\",\"port scanning\",\"service identification\"],\"responsibility\":\"Identify all network-facing services and their listening ports\",\"allowed_tools\":[\"shell\"],\"token_budget\":50000,\"target_host\":null},{\"role_name\":\"Container Services Specialist\",\"expertise\":[\"docker\",\"podman\",\"container runtimes\"],\"responsibility\":\"Check for containerized services and container runtime status\",\"allowed_tools\":[\"shell\"],\"token_budget\":50000,\"target_host\":null}],\"tasks\":[{\"title\":\"Identify Init System and System Services\",\"description\":\"Determine which init system is in use (systemd, SysV, upstart, etc.) and list all services managed by it. For systemd: 'systemctl list-units --type=service --state=running'. For SysV: 'service --status-all'. Also check running processes with 'ps aux' to catch services not managed by init system.\",\"assigned_role\":\"System Services Auditor\",\"depends_on\":[],\"priority\":1,\"hypothesis\":\"H1: System uses systemd as primary init system\"},{\"title\":\"Check Listening Network Services\",\"description\":\"Use 'ss -tulpn' or 'netstat -tulpn' to identify all listening ports and the processes/services using them. Cross-reference with process list to identify service names. Include both TCP and UDP services.\",\"assigned_role\":\"Network Services Investigator\",\"depends_on\":[],\"priority\":1,\"hypothesis\":\"H4: Network services might be running but not showing in standard service lists\"},{\"title\":\"Investigate Container Runtime Status\",\"description\":\"Check if Docker is installed and running: 'systemctl status docker' or 'docker ps'. Check for Podman: 'podman ps'. List all running containers and their exposed ports. Also check for other container runtimes like containerd.\",\"assigned_role\":\"Container Services Specialist\",\"depends_on\":[],\"priority\":2,\"hypothesis\":\"H2: Multiple container runtimes might be present\"},{\"title\":\"Check for Traditional Init Services\",\"description\":\"If systemd is not present, check for SysV init scripts in /etc/init.d/ and their status. Also check for upstart if applicable. Verify with 'service --status-all' or by examining /etc/init.d directory.\",\"assigned_role\":\"System Services Auditor\",\"depends_on\":[\"Identify Init System and System Services\"],\"priority\":3,\"hypothesis\":\"H3: Traditional init systems might be in use on older systems\"},{\"title\":\"Compile Comprehensive Service Report\",\"description\":\"Combine findings from all investigations into a single report. Categorize services by: 1) System-managed services (systemd/SysV), 2) Network services with ports, 3) Containerized services, 4) Standalone processes. Include service names, PIDs, ports, and status.\",\"assigned_role\":\"System Services Auditor\",\"depends_on\":[\"Identify Init System and System Services\",\"Check Listening Network Services\",\"Investigate Container Runtime Status\",\"Check for Traditional Init Services\"],\"priority\":4,\"hypothesis\":\"All services can be categorized into system-managed, network-facing, containerized, or standalone processes\"}],\"synthesis_strategy\":\"The System Services Auditor will compile results from all agents into a unified report. Data will be cross-referenced to eliminate duplicates (e.g., a systemd service that also appears in network scan). The final output will be a categorized list showing: 1) Init system identified, 2) System-managed services with status, 3) Network services with ports and protocols, 4) Containerized services, 5) Other running processes that appear to be services. Any discrepancies or unusual findings will be highlighted.\"}","tokens_used":null,"hmac":"7fbc01a7c791ff07db0a87c7e09412f619773e8a69e800aa7f1b86c29e176141"}
